               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="codex">
                     <supportDesc material="chart">
                        <support>Paper with watermark. <watermark>The watermark consists of two
                              coats of arms, one on top of the other. The one on top can be
                              identified as the coat of arms of Palatinate and Bavaria, whereas the
                              one below this is a coat of arms with a crowned man's head and the
                              letters I and S (e.g. fols 1 and 8, 3 and 6, 9 and 14, 11 and 12.).
                              There is no countermark.</watermark>
                        </support>
                        <extent>14. <dimensions type="leaf" scope="all">
                              <height unit="mm" quantity="181">181</height>
                              <width unit="mm" atLeast="140" atMost="145">140-145</width>
                           </dimensions>.</extent>
                        <foliation>
                           <p>Later foliation 1-14 in grey ink in the upper right-hand corners.</p>
                        </foliation>
                        <collation>
                           <p>The manuscript consists of two quires.<list>
                                 <item>I: fols. 1-8 (1+8, 2+7, 3+6, 4+5)</item>
                                 <item>II: fols. 9-14 (9+14, 10+13, 11+12)</item>
                              </list>
                           </p>
                           <catchwords> There are catchwords in the bottom right-hand corners of
                              most pages, except from fols 2v, 8r and 12v.</catchwords>
                        </collation>
                        <condition>
                           <p>The outer margins are severely damaged (bite marks on the bottom outer
                              edges). The damage most certainly postdates the trimming of the leaves
                              but predates the binding.</p>
                           <p>The bottom margin of fol. 9 is also slightly damaged.</p>
                           <p>The upper outer corner of fol. 11 was repaired with Japanese
                              tissue.</p>
                           <p>A piece of paper was once appended to the outer margin of fol. 1r, but
                              it is now mostly removed.</p>
                           <!-- ??? -->
                           <p>Some leaves are stained.</p>
                           <p>The leaves are slighlty discoloured, mostly around the edges.</p>
                        </condition>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout columns="1" writtenLines="15 17">
                           <p>The manuscript is written in one column with 15-17 lines per page and
                              4-6 words per line.</p>
                           <p>The written area measures ca. <dimensions type="written">
                                 <height unit="mm" quantity="130">130</height>
                                 <width unit="mm" atLeast="85" atMost="90"
                                 >85-90</width></dimensions>.</p>
                        </layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc hands="1">
                     <handNote scribe="unknown" scope="sole" script="kurrent">
                        <p>The entire manuscript was written by one unknown scribe. The text is
                           written in kurrent script, while rubrics are written in chancery
                           script.</p>
                     </handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <decoDesc>
                     <decoNote type="initial">Pen-flourished initials in the rubrics and at the
                        beginning of sections executed with black ink (1-2 lines). Most of these
                        initials in the rubrics are decorated with squiggles and fine loops (e.g.
                        1r:1). The beginning of each paragraph is marked by differently decorated
                        initials which partly resemble the initials used for the headings (1-3
                        lines, e.g. 2v, 3r).</decoNote>
                  </decoDesc>
                  <additions>
                     <p>Marginal bibliographical note on 8r (written by the scribe) referring to
                           <title type="uniform">The Provincial Law of Jutland</title> but is partly
                        illegible due to severe damage to the outer margins.</p>
                  </additions>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding contemporary="false" notBefore="1771" notAfter="1780">
                        <p>Cardboard binding covered by handmade grey paper (<dimensions
                              type="binding"><height unit="mm" quantity="188">188</height>
                              <width unit="mm" atLeast="144" atMost="147"
                              >144-147</width></dimensions>). A label at the top of the spine (from
                              <name type="person" key="KriKaa001">Kålund</name>'s time) states the
                           shelfmark <!-- and the name of the collection  ? -->. At the foot of the
                           spine the remainder of a white label, once containing the running title,
                           is found. The cover is slightly dirty and show traces of use.</p>
                        <p>On the upper board, <q>No 38. B Skaanske Kirche Loug.</q> is written in
                           black ink. Orignally, the letter of the shelfmark was <q>A</q>, but it
                           was later crossed out and substituted with a superscript <q>B</q> in
                           lighter brown ink.</p>
                        <p>The manuscript is stored in one box together with <ref
                              target="#AM04-0038-a-en">AM 38 a 4to</ref>.</p>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
                  <accMat>
                     <p>Old cords which were removed from the binding are stored in the same box as
                        the manuscripts.</p>
                  </accMat>
               </physDesc>
               <history>

                  <origin notBefore="1640" notAfter="1660" cert="medium" evidence="external">
                     <p>Written in <origPlace key="DK">Denmark</origPlace>. Kålund (<bibl><ref
                              type="secondary-1" target="KKKat">Katalog</ref><biblScope
                              unit="volume">I</biblScope><biblScope unit="pages"
                           >365</biblScope></bibl>) dates it to the seventeenth century.</p>
                     <p>A narrower dating is provided by Schlyter (<bibl><ref target="CorpJur9"
                              >Corpus juris Sveo-Gotorum antiqui: Codex juris Scanici</ref>
                           <biblScope unit="volume">IX</biblScope>
                           <biblScope unit="page">xcix</biblScope></bibl>, who dated it to the
                           <origDate notBefore="1640" notAfter="1660">the middle of the seventeenth
                           century</origDate>.</p>
                  </origin>
                  <provenance>
                     <p>At some point part of a larger manuscript, which was subsequently divided into two units:
                           <ref type="ms" target="#AM04-0038-a-en">AM 38 a 4to</ref> and AM 38 b
                        4to.</p>
                     <p>In <name type="person" key="JonOla003">Jón Ólafsson</name>'s catalogue from
                        <date when="1730">1730</date> '38 in 4to' was described as a single manuscript,
                        but there is no indication of two copies.</p>
                  </provenance>
               </history>
